can be acquired by anyone willing to make the effort, say the authors. And, through case studies of a variety of organizations, they emphasize that all members of productive groups must be ready to take the lead when their specific skills are most relevant to the problem at hand. The authors analyze how organizations and individuals can adopt this new leadership mode, and they discuss the results of a recent survey of leadership ideas and attitudes among active environmental leaders. Shifting emphasis away from celebrated leaders on the world stage, Gordon and Berry focus on "essential" leadership-the kind that engages each member of an organization on an everyday basis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aConservation leadershipxStudy and teaching (Higher)zUnited States. 0aEnvironmental responsibilityxStudy and teaching (Higher)zUnited States. 0aLeadershipxStudy and teaching (Higher)zUnited States. 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh1 aBerry, Joyce K., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aChristensen, Norman L.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300132977423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300132977.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles